      <section id="resources">
        <!-- Homepage Content -->
        <h2>RESOURCES</h2>
        <p> National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA): Provides statistics, research, and campaigns focused on road safety and preventing drink driving. (Website: nhtsa.gov)

            Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD): Offers education, victim support, and advocacy against drink driving. (Website: madd.org)
            
            Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC): Offers data, research, and resources on the impact of alcohol-impaired driving. (Website: cdc.gov)
            
            Ride-Sharing Apps: Platforms like Uber and Lyft provide safe transportation alternatives, reducing the need for drink driving.
            
            Local Law Enforcement Agencies: Contact local police departments for information on local laws, penalties, and community programs related to drink driving.
            
            Healthcare Providers: Doctors and health professionals can offer guidance on alcohol consumption and its effects on driving.
            
            Alcohol Education Programs: These may be available through schools, community centers, or online platforms, providing information on responsible drinking and its impact on driving.
            
            Community Support Groups: Organizations or groups focused on road safety and alcohol prevention might offer resources and support for individuals and communities.
            
            Government Websites: National and regional government websites often provide resources, laws, and statistics related to drink driving and road safety.
            
            Alcohol Treatment Centers: For those struggling with alcohol dependency, treatment centers can offer support and resources to overcome addiction and prevent drink driving incidents.</p>            
